// We have the integral \(\frac{1}{2\pi i} \int_C \frac{\cos z}{\sin z}dz\), where \(C\) is the circle \(|z|=5\).
// The integrand is \(\frac{\cos z}{\sin z}\), which simplifies to \(\cot z\).
// We need to use the residue theorem to evaluate this integral.
// The function \(\cot z\) has simple poles at \(z = n\pi\) for integers \(n\), but only \(z = \pi\) and \(z = -\pi\) lie inside the circle \(|z|=5\).

// The residue of \(\cot z\) at \(z = \pi\) and \(z = -\pi\) is both 1 because \(\cot z = \frac{\cos z}{\sin z}\) and \(\sin(\pi) = 0\), \(\sin(-\pi) = 0\), and \(\cos(\pi) = -1\), \(\cos(-\pi) = -1\).
// So, the residues are \(\frac{\cos(\pi)}{\cos(\pi)} = -1\) and \(\frac{\cos(-\pi)}{\cos(-\pi)} = -1\), but since it is \(\frac{1}{\sin(z)}\cos(z)\), it is actually 1.

// According to the residue theorem, the integral is \(2\pi i\) times the sum of residues inside the contour.
// Thus, the sum of residues is 1 + 1 = 2, and the integral is \(2\pi i \cdot 2 = 4\pi i\).

// So the value of the original integral is \(\frac{1}{2\pi i} \cdot 4\pi i = 2\).

