\lim_{n \to \infty} n \int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}} (1-\sin x)^n \, dx &= \lim_{n \to \infty} n \int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}} e^{n \ln(1-\sin x)} \, dx \\
&= \lim_{n \to \infty} n \int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}} e^{-n \sin x} \, dx \\
&= \lim_{n \to \infty} n \left[ \int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{4}} e^{-n \sin x} \, dx + \int_{\frac{\pi}{4}}^{\frac{\pi}{2}} e^{-n \sin x} \, dx \right].
\end{align*}

Since $\sin x \leq x$ for $x \in [0, \frac{\pi}{4}]$, and $\sin x \geq \sin(\frac{\pi}{2} - x) = \cos x$ for $x \in [\frac{\pi}{4}, \frac{\pi}{2}]$, the first integral tends to $0$ as $n \to \infty$, and the second integral can be transformed as follows:

\begin{align*}
\lim_{n \to \infty} n \int_{\frac{\pi}{4}}^{\frac{\pi}{2}} e^{-n \sin x} \, dx &= \lim_{n \to \infty} n \int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{4}} e^{-n \cos x} \, dx &\text{(using the substitution } x = \frac{\pi}{2} - u) \\
&= \lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{n}{\cos^2 x} \int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{4}} \cos x \cdot e^{-n \cos x} \, dx \\
&= \lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{n}{\cos^2 x} \cdot \frac{1}{n} \\
&= \lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{1}{\cos^2 x} = \frac{1}{\cos^2 \left( \frac{\pi}{4} \right)} = \frac{1}{\left( \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \right)^2} = 2.
\end{align*}

따라서 극한값은 $\boxed{2}$입니다.
